,Recommended,244030,7319057,"Posted: 5 October, 2013",all,orb,"It's your own Mars (and asteroid belt) Exploration Program simulator.In the game you control probes or rovers in real time (unlike in real life, where their control sequences are preprogrammed, and in emergency they are automatically put in a safe mode). It isn't only about exploring Mars, but also its moons and asteroids. You can also operate rover on Earth.The objectives are quite repetitive (ride there, shoot photos, analyze air, soil, rocks, take a sample, all this to get funds and unlock next levels of available hardware which you will send to Mars next), but it isn't a boring game. You need to be careful to not break the equipment (or wheels), and watch out for strong wind, as small rovers and probes are quite light and fragile. It's currently in active development, so some things may still change and a new content (like sample analyze results currently having a placeholder) will be added.It's a great game for space geeks, people who like realistic vehicle simulators, and other people who want to view Mars from rover's perspective."
76561198016121382,Not Recommended,244030,29807700,Posted: 9 February,all,[TFB] Jax The Reaper,"I have 92 hours of play time in Take On Mars.This is the only review I've done since joining steam 8 years ago. I can not in good conscience allow this game to be released without saying anything. This game was not and still is not ready for release. It is still full of bugs and crashes a lot. I've tried so many work arounds I've seen on the forum and elsewhere to stop this from happening but to no avail. Personally, I feel like I shouldn't have to do something like all that just to get the game to work at it's basic level.The game crashes when you try to scroll with the mouse wheel. It also crashes when exiting to the main menu. The worst crash for me, is when you try to overwrite a save, the game crashes without saving and deletes your current save on top of that.I think a fair amount of the issues could be temporarily remedied by incorperating an auto-save feature into the game. Or even a quick save button. Like just pressing F5 to save for example. As it stands, you have to go through a few menus just to save. It gets tedious to do this every five minutes in case the game decides to randomly crash. Then you wouldn't lose hours worth of work when it does.The discussion forum is full of threads about crashing issues. A lot of people can't even get the game to start running. I've spent hours going back through the thread's and I've come to the conclusion that these developers put the game into release to make one last cash grab and then wash their hands of it.And this game is certainly not worth the 26.99 they want for it. Discounting the problems this game has, I would say with how basic it is, it's worth maybe 10 to 15 dollars at most. I really regret the 30 dollars I spent on it a few years ago.The thing that really bugs me the most about this game is the power production. I had to download a mod increasing the power production of the nuclear reactor just to be able to play. In the vanilla game, you have to build 11 nuclear reactors to power one simple device continuously. With resources as scarce as they are in the game, that is just rediculous. And solar panels are a joke because they produce even less power and obviously none at night. And the night lasts far longer than the day. And there are no batteries you can make to store power for use at night so wasting resources to build solar panels is pointless.TL;DRThis game is an obvious bug/crash fest and cash grab. The devs obviously want to wash their hands of it. Please, protect your hard earned income and do not buy it."
,Recommended,244030,9886940,"Posted: 20 April, 2014",all,neddread,"""My God, it's full of stars!""I have had this game since the early versions and even then it felt like a shop ready product and not early access, and the new updates have just felt like free DLC.The screen shots tell the story of the graphics, they are awesome, and the whole game looks like that.The realism is, well I've never sent a probe to Mars, but it feels pretty bleeding real to me. And the realism is the key to your enjoyment of this title.If you want fast paced action on a future Mars then move along (I've seen posts saying it's boring, pah!).If you're like me and absorb yourself into a sim about the current exploration of Mars, with all the slow analysis of rocks and atmosphere and the chance to take photos that look very similar to NASA pics that comes with that then buy this game, clear about a month in your schedule and prepare for a real, scientific and indepth exploration of our solar cousin.As real as it gets. Stunning sim. 11/10."
