,Recommended,244030,28445040,"Posted: 18 December, 2016",all,Llordllama,"I bought Take on Mars (TKOM) a couple of years ago, following an article in PCG, while it was early in it's early access phase.  It was at the time monstrously, hideously, gloriously broken.  How broken you ask?  Well, most of the main game didn’t work and while there was a game engine for clamouring around on Mars, trying to build anything usually resulted in catapulting fragments of base hundreds of meters away.  Your character on Mars also lumbered about like an arthritic pensioner in the final stages of terminal collapse, and it crashed at the merest hint of a physics-object conflict.And yet…I kept playing it.  Slowly, glacially slowly, updates came out.  Months went by at one point where a build made it impossible to play at all.  Most games like this, I’d have shrugged, written off the purchase price as an object lesson in looking before I lept and moved on.  But I’ve never uninstalled it, and periodically, between games of GTA, Kerbal and Metal Gear, I’d pop back to Mars to see how things were going.As a result of my continued curiosity, I’ve somehow managed to sink over 60 hours into this game now, and rising.  It is still, safe to say, far from polished.  Movement is still a challenge.  Building anything before starving to death or running out of essential minerals, certainly in the core ‘manned exploration’ missions is a Sisyphean struggle.  But it DOES payback in spades in giving you that feeling of being the first person on Mars, exploring in a hostile environment.  Survival SHOULD be challenging, and every minor victory feels like a grand slam.  Didn’t starve to death before getting the mobile lab down?  VICTORY!  Managed to work out how to build a working, modular 3D printer? VICTORY!  Damn…out of resources to build anything else though…Don’t buy this game if you’re lucking for something easy to play, honestly hours can be sucked in and you’ll only make teeny, tiny progress.  But what progress you, and the developers, make in TKOM, will really feel satisfying!  See you on the dawn side…"
