76561198094935797,Recommended,244030,21994030,"Posted: 22 March, 2016",all,[M.A.C.O.] Schrödinger,"--For those wanting to just get to a hands on review skip to the secondary section.--I have been watching and following, and in the past had time to help with hunting bugs and harassing the devs with copy pasted reports since it first came out on early access. Over time I have gotten to see this game grow more and more, thus expanding it's own potential. Take On Mars not only is a simulator, but an educational platform (Hence the wiki data you unlock in the Robotics portion.). With games like this, and Kerbal Space Program, I see a lot of potential for games to bring new challenges and focus to many forms of education in simulation that can even be utilized in classrooms to get kids interested in space exploration, physics, astrobiology, and aeronautics through adaptive and hands on learning.I know it's been a long time, and yes the due date has been pushed back, and yes there are still bugs that need to be smashed. But in the end, Take On Mars will be a perfect platform for both simulation lovers, and Mars Enthusiasts as the work put into this makes it one of the most unique games currently in beta. Long strides have been made in gaming technology that opens up more intuitive and complex forms of learning and adapting to in game demands through user comprehension and skill. This game needs as much notice and support as possible.------------------------------------------------Section Two--------------------------------------Take On Mars is a game based on the research of Mars in understanding what is to be expected for human crews to work with. In the first portion you are able to utilize probes, lander, rovers, and advanced equipment to study the martian surface and gather real world intel based on scientific findings. In chapter two you will take the role of a surviving astronaut who has to survive on the surface through building and maintaining equipment (Chapter2 is still in development.)Also there are singleplayer and multiplayer scenarios, along with an editor so that you can build your own scenario and upload it to the workshop. Along with this is the ability to easily mod the game files via the developer toolset if you're into that. This gives grounds so a lot of malleability to the game and what players can do with it. Overall, despite it being unfinished I have to give it a 8/10 for both the improvements, the dev team, and the uniqueness of the game. There are others sure, like Mars: Challenger, which is fun but not one I can honestly recommend.All in all, Take On Mars is a gem, and to those wondering if it is worth buying I will say this:If you don't mind putting in the effort to submit bug reports, push the game mechanics, and test different aspects of the game then yes, buy it and help the developers expand and debug more of it.If you want something polished off the bat and are not patient or willing to aid in development, then no, and nor should you buy any game on Early Access because that is what it is for."
76561198004178304,Not Recommended,244030,29936695,Posted: 14 February,all,dexnom_ᛒᛏᛃᚾᚹᚾ,"i like this game..realy do...but..it is disgrace in first place, bec bugy as hell. nu,ber of bugs is enormous and yet they released it.save your money and dont buy, you will be only frustrated and♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥"
,Recommended,244030,18438944,"Posted: 11 October, 2015",all,Blake,"I'm a fan of the survival genre. I'm a fan of the science-fiction genre. Put those two together and you get Take on Mars.While not completely finished, as denotes it's Beta Build, it is on it's way to becoming a remarkably accurate simulator (with obvious gameplay exceptions) of survival on Mars.That being said... it does suffer similar problems to most Open World Sandbox games of the same ilk at the moment. Notably the 'nothing to do but survive' problem. At least in most scenarios. Take On Mars, however, seems to address this problem with the Scenario / Scenario Editor... you can utilise triggers, events, etc. to create a story arc style of play. From landing, base building, to extraction should you want it, and thus solve the major issues of the survive to survive most survival genre titles have.What strikes me most about this game in either the Single or Multiplayer, is the emptiness. Some put it down as a Con, I put it down as a Pro... Mars is empty. There is very little to do there in reality, and this is refelcted somewhat by gameplay. However, the inclusion of science experiments, sampling, and more would add greatly to the overall experience.You can 'fake' science with the previously mentioned Scenario Triggers, but this pales in comparison to what the developers could possibly do in terms of story arc.Single Player - The Single Player Gameplay starts with what could be considered a 'modern space age' where you send probes, landers and rovers to Mars, Deimos, and even the Asteroid Belt. After 'completing' this portion of the campaign gathering all the outlined data under objectives, you are ready to launch your manned mission.I don't want to spoil the storyline of this mission arc, but Mark Watney move over, there's a new King of Mars. And it is story driven, though limited in scope. Starting in one area, and moving to another. With no option to alter which starting area, nor where you head to.If you're looking for a completely free-roam Open World Sandbox game, this one is not for you. If you're looking for a game that throws enough realism in your face to be accounted a 'true' survival game then this is the one for you.The team seems dedicated to keeping updates flowing, and they do address problems with the product as they can.The game has been in Early Access for a while, but this doesn't phase me in the slightest. Years in development is basically any title that has something unique about it, or needs to be built in a different way from previous titles. Comparing development times of a game like this to games such as Battlefield or Call of Duty wastes time, and mental energy. Building onto previously formulae (Battlefield, Call of Duty, <insert other franchise here>) will always be faster, easier, and more efficient than creating something new, and I prefer the effectiveness of Take On Mars to the fast development that would see it be a reskin of another title.In conclusion, the game does have bugs, and some of its elements lack polish, but if the development team continues the way they are going it may well show a new way to experience survival that actually throws whatever it can at you to make you fail, without big green aliens, zombies, or other post apocalyptic horrors."
76561198031374078,Not Recommended,244030,33341905,Posted: 7 July,all,Martyn169,"Bought this game a year ago thinking it would be a sort of mans first steps on mars simulation and it is to some degree, however the problem is that they have focused so much on the simulation aspect that it gets very boring and repetitive, especially in the campaign on both manned and unmanned missions. For starters in the unmanned campaign after a while you have a small rover that moves at the same speed as an asthmatic old man with parkinsons disease, you then need to travel for several miles and over an hour just to reach your destination to collect data and stuff, rather than having a system of plotting a course and letting it follow that course. You then have to repeat this several times to get the money required to unlock new parts, eventually i got to the large rover and got so bored I quit and went into the manned campaign. The manned campaign i then discovered is much the same with rubbish physics where you can be killed or knocked out when in the airlock of your truck, or by any other means for very little reason. The buttons are also hard to press and you'll press the wrong ones allot, sometimes ending in your death. Eventually I reached the point where I managed to get the refinery and drills, however i had been killed so many times by the airlock in my truck that I eventually quit the game.Would I recommend this game? not really as there are other games such as space engineers that do the game part much better, however if you want something thats a hard core sim then probably yes. I can also recommend the Scenarios and the editor in this game as some of them can be quite fun.Edit: If you really want this game I would advise you to watch some videos on it before making your decision, that goes for every other game aswell."
