,Recommended,244030,11493841,"Posted: 31 July, 2014",all,krank23,"I don't even have the words to describe how much I like this game...Or, you know, ""game"". Not sure if the word applies, but I'm going to use it anyway.Here's what you do: Send stuff to mars. On mars, you control stuff like the wheels on rovers, various cameras and scientific equipment etc. Everything is very slow-paced. You have specific missions that tell you to photograph certain features, test the atmosphere at a specific locations, etc. There are no enemies. There is very little challenge... Except it reuires a very specific type of mind to enjoy spending half an hour driving a tiny rover a few hundre meters of more or less featureless desert to take a few photographs, maybe a soil sample, then move on.Lately, more challenges have been added, which I really like. The tech tree wasn't there when I first began playing, and I enjoy trying to figure out what to research next in order to unlock the next batch of missions. It also feels like money is a bit tighter, which means a bit of budgeting and making sure you don't overextend. The vehicles run out of juice earlier as well, which means there's some challenge in trying to get as much use from each rover as possible, completing several missions before it gives up.Another kind of challenging thing is how easily things break. I've completed several missions with rovers that are missing two or more wheels (using well-known workarounds such as driving backwards)...The graphics are top notch aside from a few quirks (sometimes rocks still hover slightly above the landscape...)All in all an incredibly rewarding experience to the patient-minded who want a break from pvp and rts and fps..."
