,Recommended,244030,31911495,Posted: 22 May,all,[IBG] CaptainCheesy,"I only recommend this game really because of it's potential.The game has a numerous amount of bugs that need fixing, such as barely hitting your head and going unconscious until you die, or trying to sleep in your poptent and getting thrown under the surface of the planet just to die. I have a pretty good computer, with settings on Medium and my frames are still around 30, which tells me the game needs serious optimization. A lot of other general fixes could be implemented, but it's still a decent game.The gameplay is like no other game I've played. It's deeply immersive and rather time consuming, but this is made up for with the challenge of the game. You start out and have to find emergency oxygen dispensers to stay alive for the first 30 minutes of gameplay, as well the necessity for food and water. You have to maintain your suit from wear and damage, which is rather interesting. The managing of resources such as methane, oxygen, water, etc is none like I've seen other than State of Decay.All around, I'd give it a 3 star review, due to the excrutiatingly painful bugs it presents. Other than that, the gameplay is phenominal and would be much much much better if more content was introduced, as well as isolating and exterminating the bugs currently in game."
,Not Recommended,244030,19352622,"Posted: 28 November, 2015",all,andrewaltogether,"The developers say this will be released in February, and I have no idea how they think that will be possible. The unmanned portion seems mostly complete, but the manned portion needs at least another year. It's full of bugs and glitches, there is absolutely no tutorial, explanation, or guide anywhere, and it's lacking a lot of immersion. The bugs range from being unable to attach a power cable properly to being flung across the Martian desert because you stood on said cable the wrong way. With no explanation in-game, on the walkthroughs through Steam, or on any forum for the game, every feature is hidden until you stumble across it and major components of the game are difficult to work out. It took me three hours to figure out how to assemble a structure, and I still have no clue what any of the various utilities do. The immersion problem is one they definitely won't fix, though, because they seem pretty happy with what they have: you can hear your astronaut's breath and heartbeat. All the time. Very loudly. Right in your ear. He also can't move any faster than a slow stroll, even on Earth, and can only run ten or twenty meters before getting winded. On the Moon, you would expect to do some cool Moon-style walking like in the NASA videos, but he just casually strolls from one place to another. I got to night-time on Mars (difficult because it's 1:1 timescale and there's no way to advance time, like sleeping or waiting) and expected some sort of awe inspiring view, but it was totally unimpressive. I was more impressed the first time I got a craft into orbit in Kerbal Space Program. I have the graphics all maxed out on a mobile GPU and I get 60 FPS - that means you're not trying hard enough.From my previous experiences with this developer, I know what to expect: a game with countless flaws that showed promise and is occasionally, for very short periods, brilliant. Arma was like that, Take On Helicopters was like that, and DayZ is like that. They're very ambitious, and that's admirable, but they have no tenacity, patience, or follow-through.If you get it on sale, like I did, you'll have a fun ten hours or so before deciding to just wait for the full release. But seeing as how they say that'll be in February, I'd say you should wait until the patch/update schedule has slowed a bit, because there should be a lot of them."
