76561198041343803,Recommended,244030,31483878,Posted: 1 May,all,PioneerRun,"So far it's the only game that gives you thatMark Watney/ Mars-survival-feeling over a whole and complete campaign.I enjoyed it very much and would buy it again.(For this review I played the manned program a second time, half of it inVR, and played multiplayer scenarios).During the campaign you have to fix leaking suits, find/collect supply drops with the truck, set up devices/machines, extract resources, refine chemicals, travel to the MAV, analyze soil samples, build/puzzle 3D-printers,  to – eventually – produce fuel for your ship back to earth. You get to experience the ISS and in flashbacks the Moon too.The graphics and the atmospheric background music are really nice. The controls could be better/smoother, but you get used to it. The game is a simulation: pitch black night; correct sound (no atmosphere - no sound: well done in the air lock!); or low gravity: no crazy sprinting or driving possible!; not to mention the laborious machinery-based grinding process: electricity, chemistry, potato-horticulture... cool!Do not expect an action-packed game, or a huge ecosystem of dinosaurs to tame, or hundreds of enemies to kill. You WILL feel cast away and very lonely. It's just you against the odds on a beautiful but hostile and empty planet (similar to ""The long dark"").And every now and then, unfortunately, it's you against the physics/collision engine, that can kill you by accident (catapult you/things in the air, or smash your helmet – followed by a quick death). But with wise save-games and experience this can be overcome (single player allows reloading). Btw it adds to the survival setting – catastrophe is just around the corner.A top-up is VR: you can play TKOM with the Vive and Vorpx. It works nicely, but you need to know the menu/control system, because the inventory-font-size is too small in some cases).If you are a fan of Mark Watney it's worth buying during a sale.Read some tips and tricks to have an easier stay on Mars (see below).The game has a bigger potential (multiplayer, mods, and user made scenarios) that is sadly not being exploited much due to slow bug fixing, which disappointed the community, and made it shrink, and the reviews drop. Which is a pity because self sustaining bases are best build with other players.Similar games are in development / early access. So far TKOM is the most developed and offers the  biggest variety of features and scenarios (editor, user made content). I wish it had a modern engine and a bigger community. This way it could compete easily with the upcoming similar games and could carry itself quite some time into the future, especially with VR.Some tips and tricks (no spoilers):* always use multiple savepoints* do not jump crazy (bunny hoping)  - eventually you will fall on your visor and crack it* do not be slow: you can run out of food quickly* nights are fairly long and very dark - use your vehicle lights (there is no time lapse during sleep yet, but announced)* always stow truck ramps and stair cases before driving (can be ribbed off at rocks)* even a flat and empty water bag can block your way inside the truck cabin – keep everything tidy and crouch when it happens* its hard to move inside vehicles while having it parked on a slope* activate the mission parts to see the waypoints of the supply drops or be a very good navigator instead* the building system is not as fast as in Ark Survival due to smaller parts and real 3D printing – be patient* the object snapping works fine and is more accurate but slower in speed – be precise* resource grinding is much more challenging: think carefully about chemistry and ALL your resources at hand* never forget your helmet or do not take it off to early inside an airlock/pop tent (yes, it happens to everyone at some point in time)* plan ahead* do not forget to play some disco music ;-)Have fun - be save!"
